    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-absolute-primary",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary absolute hemolysis index validation against FDA pump in vitro dataset",
      "description": "This validation result compares CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values against in vitro measurements collected across five flow-speed operating points (2 L/min at 3500 RPM, 3 L/min at 3500 RPM, 4 L/min at 3500 RPM, 4 L/min at 2500 RPM, and 6 L/min at 2500 RPM) using the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump benchmark geometry. Blood analog (porcine erythrocytes, hematocrit 30±2%) was recirculated for 150 minutes per run; NIH was measured gravimetrically using the modified Harboe spectrophotometric method. Three independent experimental replicates were conducted per operating point. CFD predictions employed the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model integrated along pathlines from a Lagrangian particle-tracking post-processor. The simulation campaign used 12 million hexahedral cells (Grid 3 in the convergence study), second-order upwind discretisation, and the k-omega SST turbulence closure. Monte Carlo perturbation of the three power-law model constants (C, alpha, beta) over ±15% uniform distributions produced 500 CFD evaluations per operating point using Latin hypercube sampling. Predicted NIH fell within experimental uncertainty bands at 4 of 5 operating points; the 6 L/min / 2500 RPM condition showed a 12% over-prediction that remains within the 95th-percentile Monte Carlo interval. The validation comparison is considered acceptable for the COU given the acknowledged model-form limitation at high-flow off-design conditions. No structured Activity node is registered in the provenance graph for this result; the experimental and simulation campaign details are captured in this narrative only.",
